1. Introduction

As an National Basketball Association (NBA) fan, it is easy to get caught up in the percentage of field goals made by players. When a player like Lebron James drops 30+ points on a rival team, who wouldnt want to talk about the points scored. But what about the number of field goals attempted? How does a players position and role on the court, along with their age, affect the amount of his attempted field goals? You can learn a lot about a players agility and playing IQ by looking at the amount of field goals he attempts to makes, which is why I decided to base my study around it. Field goals are defined as how many shots a player makes, and field goals attempted is how many shots a player attemps to make, therefore this value is typically larger. My research question is whether a players position and age affects their field goal attempts (FGA). In basketball there are five main positions: Center, Small Forward, Point Guard, Power Forward and Shooting Guard. Within these positions players have a unique role and skillset on the court that allow them to be a vital part of the team. During the 80s and 90s, these roles were more restrictive; you rarely saw a center do anything else but rebound, assist, and defend. Nowadays, we have centers such as Nikola Joki averaging 29 points per game, along with having the most triple-doubles of the 2022-2023 season. So it is as though your position on the court correlates less with how a players FGA. I choose to look at age and how it affects field goal attempts because age correlates to experience within the NBA. Therefore the older you are, the more experience you have had in the NBA.

The data set I used is a compilation of player statistics from the NBA 2022-2023 regular seasons National Basketball Association player. This data set included each players name, position, age, average field goals made per game, average field goals attempted per game, and more.

The outcome variable for this study is field goals attempted, which I decided to focus on for the reasons stated above. There are two explanatory variables: position and age.

3. Multiple Linear Regression

3.1 Methods

The components of my multiple linear regression are:

  1. Outcome variable \[y\] = Average Field Goal Attempts
  2. Numerical explanatory data \[x_1\] = Age
  3. Categorical explanatory data \[x_2\] = Position

where the unit of analysis is players in the NBA 2022-2023 regular season.

3.3 Interpreting the Regression table (equation)

The regression equation for average field goals attempted is the following: \[\widehat{y}\] = \[field goals attempted = 2.2852 + 0.094(Age) + 1.821(PG) + 2.922(PF) + 1.536(SF) + 1.919(SG)\]

This intercept (\[2.2852\]) represents the average field goals attempted when the student isnt a point guard, power forward, small forward, or shooting guard and the age is 0.

The estimate for the slope of age of player (\[0.094\]) is associated with change in average FGA per game depending on the players position. Therefore, for every one year increase in age, there was an associate increase in FGA per game 0.0914 shots.

The estimates for the four other positions are the offsets in intercept relative to the baseline group (centers). Therefore Point Guards shoot 1.821 more shots than Centers, Power Forwards shoot 2.922 more shots than Centers, Small Forwards shoot 1.536 more shots than Centers, and Shooting Guards shoot 1.919 more shots than Centers.

4. Discussion

4.1 Conclusion

Based on section 3.3 there is no significant difference in the amount of field goals that were attempted based on position, but interestingly enough, as age increases the amount of FGA increases as well. On average, the amount of FGA increased by ~0.1, which is not that significant of an increase. I was most surprised that age did not have a negative impact on FGA because I assumed that as you get older, you take less shots. But conducting this study allowed me to see that with more time in the NBA, and thus more experience, comes more confidence as a shooter.

Overall, these results suggest that position and age is a factor of field goal attempts. This study confirmed what I already knew to be true as a avid basketball fan, but it was surprising seeing how there was not a significant difference in FGA based on positions, highlighting the well-roundness of the average NBA player.

4.2 Limitations

One limitation to this data set is that there were some players who had dual positions on the court (ex. they are both a shooting guard and small forward). I decided to omit these players because there wasnt enough players within those dual position categories to conduct proper analysis on, therefore I was not able to include their FGA values in this study. Another limitation I had was that this data set included only regular season statistics, and not pre-season nor playoff statistics. Including FGA made by players outside of the regular seasons, would give more accurate data on the amount of FGA throughout the entire season, which is a disadvantage to players who played better outside of the regular season.

4.3 Further Questions

If I were to continue researching this topic I would be interested in see how field goals made is affected by age and position and how it differs from what I found in my study. I would also like to use data that includes prior seasons so I can conclude whether my findings have been a common trend throughout the years or a newer phenomenon.

I would also like to see how this study would play out using statistics from another countrys basketball league. Would age and position effect the FGA in Australias National Basketball League or the Basketball Africa League in the same way that it does in America?
